2 HOUSE BILL 34
1 Annotated Code of Maryland
2 (2013 Volume and 2025 Supplement)
3 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
4 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
5 Article – Environment
6 5–803.
7 (h) (1) There is a comprehensive flood management grant program within the
8 Department.
9 (2) (i) Subject to the approval of the Board of Public Works, the
10 Department may use proceeds from the State debt created to fund the comprehensive flood
11 management grant program to pay the entire cost of watershed studies pursuant to
12 subsection (b) of this section.
13 (ii) The Department may provide grants to subdivisions to pay the
14 entire cost of watershed studies when the Department delegates that responsibility
15 pursuant to subsection (b) of this section.
16 (3) (i) Subject to the approval of the Board of Public Works, the
17 Department may provide grants to subdivisions for flood control and watershed
18 management capital projects, and for the capital costs related to design, purchase, and
19 installation of automated flood warning projects, provided that the projects are consistent
20 with the plans and implementation prepared and adopted in accordance with this subtitle,
21 and provided further that each project:
22 1. Is undertaken as part of a comprehensive flood
23 management plan prepared and adopted by the subdivision; and
24 2. Is not inconsistent with any State or interjurisdictional
25 flood management plan.
26 (ii) Grants for automated flood warnings projects shall be
27 conditioned to require all affected local governing bodies to:
28 1. Adopt a specific and compatible response plan which has
29 been coordinated with local emergency management authorities and reviewed and
30 approved by the Department and the Maryland Department of Emergency Management;
31 and
32 2. Provide for financial and other commitments to properly
33 operate and maintain the project.

HOUSE BILL 34 3
1 (iii) 1. The amount of any grant made by the Department for a
2 flood control and watershed management capital project that involves only nonfederal
3 funds and meets the criteria of this subtitle shall be matched by a minimum amount of 25%
4 of project costs in local government or private funds.
5 2. For a flood control and watershed management capital
6 project that involves federal funding and meets the criteria of this subtitle:
7 A. The Department may provide up to 50% of the nonfederal
8 share of the project funding; and
9 B. Local government or private funds shall provide not less
10 than 50% of the nonfederal share of the project funding.
11 (iv) Each project application for a grant under this paragraph shall
12 be submitted to and reviewed by the State clearinghouse of the Department of Planning in
13 accordance with established clearinghouse procedures.
14 (4) (i) Subject to the approval of the Board of Public Works, the
15 Department may provide grants to subdivisions immediately after a flood for acquisition of
16 any flood damaged owner–occupied dwelling.
17 (ii) Total expenditures for grants made under this paragraph may
18 not exceed 50% of the total authorized budgeted funds in a fiscal year for grants under this
19 subsection.
20 (5) (i) The Department may award grants to subdivisions that have
21 incurred at least $1,000,000 in infrastructure damage caused by a flood event that occurred
22 on or after January 1, 2009.
23 (ii) The total amount of grants awarded by the Department to
24 subdivisions under this paragraph may:
25 1. For fiscal years 2020, 2021, and 2022, equal up to 100% of
26 the total amount of money appropriated to the comprehensive flood management program;
27 and
28 2. For fiscal year 2023 and each fiscal year thereafter, equal
29 up to 50% of the total amount of money appropriated to the comprehensive flood
30 management program.
31 (iii) A grant awarded to a subdivision under this paragraph may be:
32 1. For an amount of up to 50% of the combined cost of
33 infrastructure repairs, watershed restoration, and emergency work associated with the
34 flood event;

4 HOUSE BILL 34
1 2. Used for infrastructure repairs, watershed management,
2 or emergency protection work associated with the flood event; and
3 3. Used for expenses associated with item 2 of this
4 subparagraph that the subdivision has already incurred.
5 (iv) The Department shall prioritize awarding grants under this
6 paragraph to subdivisions in which:
7 1. Infrastructure damage occurred in an area designated by
8 the Maryland Historical Trust as an historic district; or
9 2. Infrastructure damage caused by a flood event has
10 occurred more than once within the previous 5 years.
11 (6) (I) THE DEPARTMENT MAY AWARD GRANTS TO
12 MUNICIPALITIES TO PROVIDE MATCHING FUNDS TO ASSIST WITH THE COSTS OF
13 MAKING IMPROVEMENTS TO EXISTING OPEN DRAINAGE INLETS IN ACCORDANCE
14 WITH § 4–112 OF THE LOCAL GOVERNMENT ARTICLE.
15 (II) IN EACH OF FISCAL YEARS 2029 THROUGH 2031, $250,000
16 OF THE MONEY APPROPRIATED TO THE COMPREHENSIVE FLOOD MANAGEMENT
17 GRANT PROGRAM SHALL BE USED TO AWARD GRANTS UNDER THIS PARAGRAPH.
18 (7) To receive a grant, the subdivision must participate in the national
19 flood insurance program.
20 [(7)] (8) Before awarding a grant under paragraphs (2), (3), or (4) of this
21 subsection, the Department, in cooperation with the Department of Planning, shall review
22 the flood control and watershed management operations of the applicant subdivision to
23 assure that the flood control and watershed management operations are in compliance with
24 this subtitle.
25 [(8)] (9) (i) For fiscal year 2026 and each fiscal year thereafter, the
26 Governor may include in the annual State budget an appropriation for the comprehensive
27 flood management grant program of up to $20,000,000.
28 (ii) For fiscal year 2026 and each fiscal year thereafter, at least 40%
29 of funding provided under the comprehensive flood management grant program shall be
30 used for projects located in or directly benefiting underserved or overburdened
31 communities, as defined in § 1–701 of this article.
32 (iii) Funds not awarded from the comprehensive flood management
33 grant program by the end of a fiscal year:
34 1. Shall remain in the program; and

HOUSE BILL 34 5
1 2. Are not subject to § 7–302 of the State Finance and
2 Procurement Article.
3 [(9)] (10) (i) The Department, in consultation with the Department of
4 Planning, shall adopt regulations necessary for the administration of the grant program.
5 (ii) These regulations may include:
6 1. A determination of statewide and interjurisdictional needs
7 and priorities;
8 2. Standards of eligibility for applicants and projects;
9 3. Criteria for recognition of tidal and nontidal areas;
10 4. Engineering and economic standards and alternatives;
11 and
12 5. Procedures for filing and processing contents of
13 applications.
14 Article – Local Government
15 4–112.
16 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
17 INDICATED.
18 (2) (I) “APPROVED GRATING SYSTEM” MEANS A COVER PLACED
19 OVER THE OPENING OF AN OPEN DRAINAGE INLET IN ORDER TO ALLOW
20 STORMWATER RUNOFF TO ENTER THE DRAINAGE INLET WHILE PREVENTING LARGE
21 DEBRIS FROM ENTERING THE DRAINAGE INLET.
22 (II) “APPROVED GRATING SYSTEM” INCLUDES:
23 1. A STANDARD YARD INLET;
24 2. A RAISED GRATE YARD INLET;
25 3. A TRASH RACK GRATING, PROVIDED THAT THE RACK
26 HAS AT LEAST FOUR SIDES, EACH OF WHICH IS AT LEAST AS LARGE AS THE DIAMETER
27 OF THE SURFACE OPENING; AND

6 HOUSE BILL 34
1 4. FOR NEW DRAINAGE INLETS, A PRECAST CONCRETE
2 BOX INCORPORATED INTO THE CONSTRUCTION OF THE DRAINAGE INLET.
3 (3) (I) “OPEN DRAINAGE INLET” MEANS A STRUCTURE WITH A
4 SURFACE OPENING THAT:
5 (I) 1. HAS A DIAMETER OF 12 INCHES OR MORE; AND
6 (II) 2. IS DESIGNED TO COLLECT AND DRAIN STORMWATER
7 RUNOFF.
8 (II) “OPEN DRAINAGE INLET” INCLUDES AN OPEN HEADWALL
9 STRUCTURE ATTACHED TO A CULVERT.
10 (III) “OPEN DRAINAGE INLET” DOES NOT INCLUDE:
11 1. A GRATE INLET;
12 2. A CURB INLET;
13 3. A COMBINATION CURB AND GRATE INLET;
14 4. A SURFACE–LEVEL DRAINAGE TUNNEL WITH ONLY
15 ONE SURFACE–LEVEL INLET AND ONE DIRECT SURFACE–LEVEL OUTLET;
16 5. A SLOTTED INLET; OR
17 6. A CULVERT LOCATED ON AN OPEN DRAINAGE
18 HIGHWAY.
19 (4) “PRIVATELY OWNED EXISTING OPEN DRAINAGE INLET” MEANS AN
20 INLET THAT IS LOCATED ON PRIVATE PROPERTY AND WAS INSTALLED BEFORE
21 OCTOBER 1, 2026.
22 (5) (I) “PUBLICLY OWNED EXISTING OPEN DRAINAGE INLET”
23 MEANS AN INLET OWNED AND MAINTAINED BY THE MUNICIPALITY THAT WAS
24 INSTALLED BEFORE OCTOBER 1, 2026.
25 (II) “PUBLICLY OWNED EXISTING OPEN DRAINAGE INLET” DOES
26 NOT INCLUDE INLETS:
27 1. OWNED OR MAINTAINED BY A FEDERAL ENTITY,
28 STATE ENTITY, COUNTY, OR SCHOOL BOARD; OR

HOUSE BILL 34 7
1 2. INSPECTED BY THE DEPARTMENT OF THE
2 ENVIRONMENT.
3 (B) A MUNICIPALITY MAY ENTER PRIVATE PROPERTY TO:
4 (1) COMPLETE THE INVENTORY REQUIRED UNDER SUBSECTION (C)
5 OF THIS SECTION; AND
6 (2) INSTALL AN APPROVED GRATING SYSTEM.
7 (C) (1) ON OR BEFORE JULY 1, 2027, A MUNICIPALITY SHALL INVENTORY
8 THE NUMBER AND LOCATION OF ALL PUBLICLY OWNED EXISTING OPEN DRAINAGE
9 INLETS AND PRIVATELY OWNED EXISTING OPEN DRAINAGE INLETS IN THE
10 MUNICIPALITY.
11 (2) (I) 1. ON OR BEFORE APRIL 1, 2028, A MUNICIPALITY
12 SHALL DEVELOP A PRIORITIZATION PLAN FOR MAKING IMPROVEMENTS TO
13 PUBLICLY OWNED EXISTING OPEN DRAINAGE INLETS AND PRIVATELY OWNED
14 EXISTING OPEN DRAINAGE INLETS.
15 2. THE PLAN SHALL PRIORITIZE MAKING
16 IMPROVEMENTS TO PUBLICLY OWNED EXISTING OPEN DRAINAGE INLETS AND
17 PRIVATELY OWNED EXISTING OPEN DRAINAGE INLETS THAT POSE THE GREATEST
18 RISK TO PUBLIC SAFETY.
19 3. A. A MUNICIPALITY IS NOT REQUIRED TO MAKE
20 IMPROVEMENTS TO PUBLICLY OWNED EXISTING OPEN DRAINAGE INLETS AND
21 PRIVATELY OWNED EXISTING OPEN DRAINAGE INLETS THAT DO NOT POSE A
22 LEGITIMATE RISK TO PUBLIC SAFETY.
23 B. A MUNICIPALITY SHALL INCLUDE IN THE PLAN AN
24 EXPLANATION OF THE REASON FOR EACH PUBLICLY OWNED EXISTING OPEN
25 DRAINAGE INLET AND PRIVATELY OWNED EXISTING OPEN DRAINAGE INLET
26 EXCLUDED FROM THE PRIORITIZATION PLAN.
27 (II) IMPROVEMENTS MAY INCLUDE:
28 1. INSTALLATION OF AN APPROVED GRATING SYSTEM
29 SECURED TO THE INLET END OF THE OPEN DRAINAGE INLET OR THE CONCRETE
30 STRUCTURE BUILT TO HOUSE THE DRAINAGE INLET, IN A MANNER THAT PREVENTS
31 THE APPROVED GRATING SYSTEM FROM BEING REMOVED WITHOUT THE
32 APPROPRIATE TOOLS OR BY THE FORCE OF FLOOD WATER; OR
33 2. INSTALLATION OF FENCING THAT:

8 HOUSE BILL 34
1 A. OBSTRUCTS AT LEAST 50% OF ANY OPENING; AND
2 B. IS DESIGNED AND INSTALLED IN A MANNER THAT
3 WOULD NOT ALLOW A PERSON TO ENTER THE OPEN DRAINAGE INLET.
4 (3) ON OR BEFORE APRIL 1, 2028, EACH MUNICIPALITY SHALL
5 NOTIFY A PRIVATE PROPERTY OWNER WITH A PRIVATELY OWNED EXISTING OPEN
6 DRAINAGE INLET THAT THE INSTALLATION OF AN APPROVED GRATING SYSTEM OR
7 FENCING IS REQUIRED IN ACCORDANCE WITH PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION.
8 (4) ON OR BEFORE APRIL 1, 2031, EACH MUNICIPALITY SHALL MAKE
9 IMPROVEMENTS TO ALL PUBLICLY OWNED EXISTING OPEN DRAINAGE INLETS AND
10 PRIVATELY OWNED EXISTING OPEN DRAINAGE INLETS INCLUDED IN THE
11 PRIORITIZATION PLAN DEVELOPED UNDER PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION.
12 (5) (I) A MUNICIPALITY IS RESPONSIBLE FOR THE COST OF
13 INSTALLING IMPROVEMENTS ON ALL PUBLICLY OWNED EXISTING OPEN DRAINAGE
14 INLETS AND PRIVATELY OWNED EXISTING OPEN DRAINAGE INLETS.
15 (II) A MUNICIPALITY MAY APPLY TO THE COMPREHENSIVE
16 FLOOD MANAGEMENT GRANT PROGRAM WITHIN THE DEPARTMENT OF THE
17 ENVIRONMENT TO COST–SHARE A PORTION OF THE INSTALLATION COSTS.
18 (D) A MUNICIPALITY IS NOT REQUIRED TO ADD IMPROVEMENTS TO ANY
19 PUBLICLY OWNED EXISTING OPEN DRAINAGE INLETS AND PRIVATELY OWNED
20 EXISTING OPEN DRAINAGE INLETS IF IT WOULD SIGNIFICANTLY IMPAIR THE
21 HYDRAULIC CAPACITY OF THE DRAINAGE SYSTEM.
22 (E) ONCE A MUNICIPALITY HAS INSTALLED AN APPROVED GRATING SYSTEM
23 ON A PRIVATELY OWNED EXISTING OPEN DRAINAGE INLET, THE MUNICIPALITY:
24 (1) IS NOT RESPONSIBLE FOR MAINTAINING IMPROVEMENTS
25 INSTALLED ON A PRIVATELY OWNED EXISTING OPEN DRAINAGE INLET; AND
26 (2) MAY NOT BE HELD LIABLE FOR INCIDENTS ARISING OUT OF THE
27 MAINTENANCE OF AN APPROVED GRATING SYSTEM.
28 (F) ANY NEW OPEN DRAINAGE INLET INSTALLED IN A MUNICIPALITY SHALL
29 BE EQUIPPED WITH AN APPROVED GRATING SYSTEM THAT MEETS THE
30 REQUIREMENTS FOR INSTALLATION DESCRIBED IN THIS SECTION.
31 (B) (1) SUBJECT TO PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION, A
32 MUNICIPALITY SHALL:

HOUSE BILL 34 9
1 (I) INCORPORATE AN APPROVED GRATING SYSTEM INTO THE
2 CONSTRUCTION OF ANY NEW OPEN DRAINAGE INLET WITHIN THE MUNICIPALITY;
3 AND
4 (II) INSTALL AN APPROVED GRATING SYSTEM ON ANY EXISTING
5 OPEN DRAINAGE INLET WITHIN THE MUNICIPALITY.
6 (2) AN APPROVED GRATING SYSTEM CONSTRUCTED OR INSTALLED
7 UNDER THIS SUBSECTION SHALL BE SECURED TO THE INLET END OF THE OPEN
8 DRAINAGE INLET, OR THE CONCRETE STRUCTURE BUILT TO HOUSE THE DRAINAGE
9 INLET, IN A MANNER THAT PREVENTS THE APPROVED GRATING SYSTEM FROM
10 BEING REMOVED WITHOUT THE APPROPRIATE TOOLS OR BY THE FORCE OF FLOOD
11 WATER.
12 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That, on or before June 1, 2027,
13 each municipality in the State shall install an approved grating system on any existing
14 open drainage inlet within the municipality in accordance with § 4–112 of the Local
15 Government Article, as enacted by Section 1 of this Act.
16 SECTION 3. 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
17 October 1, 2026.
Approved:
